'BjÃ¶rk GuÃ°mundsdÃ³ttir' (; Commonly pronounced . ; born 21 November
1965), known as 'BjÃ¶rk', is an Icelandic singer-songwriter. Her musical style is
eclectic and she has achieved recognition in rock, jazz, electronic dance music,
classical, and folk. [http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_e-
ntertainment/music/article3586432.ece Down time: Bjork] The Sunday Times, Robert
Sandall, 23 March 2008

Three of BjÃ¶rk's 1990s singles charted in the UK Top 10 ("It's Oh So Quiet"
reached number 4, "Army of Me" number 10, and "Hyperballad" number
8). Roberts, David. Guinness Book of British Hit Singles & Albums. Guinness
World Records Ltd 17th edition (2004), p. 60 ISBN 0-85112-199-3 Her record
label, One Little Indian, reported that by 2003 she had sold more than
15 million albums worldwide. Inside BjÃ¶rk DVD documentary (2003).
Documentary spanning BjÃ¶rk's musical career. She has won four BRIT Awards,
four MTV Video Music Awards, one MOJO Award, three UK Music Video Awards, and,
in 2010, the Polar Music Prize from the Royal Swedish Academy of Music in
recognition of her "deeply personal music and lyrics, her precise arrangements
and her unique voice."

BjÃ¶rk has also been nominated for 13 Grammy Awards (plus two for art direction
on her album sleeves, done by others), one Academy Award, and two Golden Globe
Awards. She won the Best Actress Award at the 2000 Cannes Film Festival for her
performance in [[Dancer in the Dark]]. She
was ranked thirty-sixth in VH1's "The 100 Greatest Women in Rock and
Roll," [http://www.vh1.com/shows/dyn/the_greatest/62162/episode.jhtml The
Greatest | Show Cast, Episodes, Guides, Trailers, Web Exclusives, Previews].
VH1.com. Retrieved 2011-02-28. eighth in MTV's "22 Greatest Voices in
Music," and sixtieth in Rolling Stone's "100
Greatest Singers of All Time."
